Project

House Sales Prediction Modelling

The objective of the analysis was to obtain a relationship, whereby we can predict the selling price of a house based on more than one independent variable. In the analysis below, first, it was performed on the dataset without any changes. Next, we took the log values and performed the analysis on those values. The model with the log values seems to predict the results much better than without the log values.

STEP 0 Initializing

In this step, the required libraries were loaded into RStudio. After the libraries were loaded, the dataset was loaded into the R working environment. One modification was made into the data; for the discrete text values i.e.the first 3 columns of the dataset, the values were changed to respective integer IDs. The column types were then changed to numeric for further operations onto the data.

Loading Libraries

Loading the required libraries for the analysis.

library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)
library(magrittr)
library(car)
library(MASS)

Loading the dataset.

Loading the csv file into R, and cleaning the data by removing blanks.

dataset <- read_csv("HouseSales.csv", na = c(""))
head(dataset)

### STEP 2 Correlation

In this step, the correlation matrix was plotted so as to see the relationships between different variables in the data. Region, AnnualCrimeRate and NaturalLight show relatively high values of correlation in the matrix. The matrix also helps in seeking out multicollinearity. None of the values were greater than 0.75 between any combination of variables, therefore, it was assumed that there is no multicollinearity in the data. The categorical values were converted to the numeric values for the correlation function, because it only takes numeric values for correlation.

Correlation Matrix

dataset$Region[dataset$Region == "South"] <- 1
dataset$Region[dataset$Region == "Midwest"] <- 2

dataset$Type[dataset$Type == "Single Family"] <- 1
dataset$Type[dataset$Type == "Townhouse"] <- 2

dataset$NaturalLight[dataset$NaturalLight == "Low"] <- 1
dataset$NaturalLight[dataset$NaturalLight == "Medium"] <- 2
dataset$NaturalLight[dataset$NaturalLight == "High"] <- 3

STEP 3 Regression Model

In this step, a model was established for the given data to predict selling price of the house. The summary of the model was used to get a measure of how feasible our model is. Two values from the summary were of main concern, the p-value and the adjusted R-squared value. After trying out different models, the following model was selected. This model gave a R squared value of 0.372 and a p-value of less than 0.05.

Modelling and Summary

model1 <- lm(`Selling Price` ~ Region + Type + AnnualCrimeRate, data = dataset)
summary(model1)

STEP 4 Non-Linearity

In this step, the crPlot() command was used to test the non-linearity of the residuals. Since the distance between the residual line and the component line was not significant, it was assumed that predictors have a linear relationship with the dependent variable. The plot is shown below the code chunk.

Testing for Non-Linearity

crPlots(model1)

STEP 5 Non-Normality

Testing for Non-Normality

This step included testing for non-normality of the residuals. The points deviate from the line, therefore, we can say that there is some non-normality in the model. The distribution of the studentized residuals show that most of the data can be assumed normal, if the outlier is not taken into consideration.

qqPlot(model1, main="QQ Plot") 

## [1] 1 7
sresid <- studres(model1)
hist(sresid, freq=FALSE, main="Distribution of Studentized Residuals")

STEP 6 HOMOSCEDASTICITY

This step involved testing for homoscedasticity. For this model, the p-value is 0.014, which is less than 0.05. Therefore, our model is more likely to be heteroscedastic. The spread graph below confirms the model to be heteroscedastic. But since the difference is not too much, and the R-squared value getting lower with homoscedastic results, we assumed it to be a trade-off between both values.

Testing for homoscdasticity

ncvTest(model1)
## Non-constant Variance Score Test 
## Variance formula: ~ fitted.values 
## Chisquare = 6.012578, Df = 1, p = 0.014204
spreadLevelPlot(model1)

## 
## Suggested power transformation:  -0.006971636

STEP 7 INFLUENCE PLOT

In this step, the influence plot was obtained as shown below:

Influence plot

influencePlot(model1, id.method="identify", main="Influence Plot", sub="Circle size is proportional
to Cook's Distance", id=list(method="identify") )

STEP 8 MULTICOLLINEARITY

The last step for the model was used to get a measure of multicollinearity in the model. Since the Vifs are smaller than 4, we can assume that there is no multicollinearity in the model.

Testing for multicollinearity

vif(model1)
##          Region            Type AnnualCrimeRate 
##        1.591470        1.033369        1.564926

Since the model was not impressive, the next approach we used was taking the log of the variables and creating the model with newer variables. The same steps were followed for the model below. The model used 4 variables, and reported a R-squared value of 0.772, with p-value less than 0.05.

For the residuals, the crPlot showed almost overlapping residual and component lines, and the distance between residuals and line in QQ plot was not significant. The distribution plot shows the data to be almost normal, and the reported p-value for the residuals was greater than 0.05. The Vifs were also less than 4, so all the assumptions pointed towards a better model for predicting house prices.

The codes and the plots of this model are shown below. The steps followed are similar to the case in the first model.

dataset<-log(dataset)
model1 <- lm(`Selling Price` ~ Type + `Lot Cost` + NaturalLight+ AnnualCrimeRate, data = dataset)
summary(model1)
